df = pd.read_csv("raw.csv")

# Data Cleanup and Preprocessing
# Leave only dates and close values.
df = df.iloc[3:, [0] + [6*i + 4 for i in range(4)]]
date = pd.to_datetime(df.iloc[:,0]).rename("date", inplace=True)
# initialize new dataframe
df = pd.DataFrame({"date": date,
                    "SPX": df["^GSPC.3"],
                    "VIX": df["^VIX.3"],
                    "SSE": df["000001.SS.3"],
                    "CNY": df["CNYUSD=X.3"]})
df.set_index(df["date"], drop=True, inplace=True)
df = df.dropna(axis=0, how="any")

# Manual correction of error entry 
# for this particular date in Yahoo Finance data.
# Replaced with data from investing.com
df.loc["2011-07-18", "CNY"] = 0.1546

# preserve date range Series for log-return dataframe.
date = df["date"]
del df["date"]

for col in df.columns:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')

sns.relplot(kind="line", data=df[["SPX","SSE"]])
sns.relplot(kind="line", data=df["VIX"])
sns.relplot(kind="line", data=df["CNY"])

# Convert daily close quotes to one-day-ahead log returns in percentages
def getLogReturns(quotes):
    return [100 * np.log(quotes[i] / quotes[i-1])
           for i in range(1, len(quotes))]

df_lret = pd.DataFrame(columns=df.columns, index=date[1:])
for col in df_lret.columns:
    df_lret[col] = getLogReturns(df[col].tolist())
    sns.relplot(kind="line", data=df_lret[col])

#Tests
# Augmented Dickey-Fuller: non-stationary
def adf(timeseries, title, cutoff=0.01):
    result = False
    
    print('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test for: ' + title)
    dftest = sm.tsa.stattools.adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    
    pvalue = dftest[1]
    if pvalue < cutoff:
        print('p-value = %.6f. The series is likely stationary.' % pvalue)
        result = True
    else:
        print('p-value = %.6f. The series is likely non-stationary.' % pvalue)

    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print(dfoutput)
    print()
    
    return result

for v in resultsdb.values():
    data = v[1]
    print(v[0] + ": \n")
    for col in data.columns:
        title = " - ".join((v[0], col))
        adf(data[col], title)
        print()

# Apply second-order differencing to non-stationary data
def getSecondOrderLogReturns(quotes):
    return [100 * np.log((quotes[i] / quotes[i-1]) / (quotes[i-1] / quotes[i-2]))
           for i in range(2, len(quotes))]

#df.loc["2019-11-25":"2019-12-01"].head()
CRdf_lret["SPX"] = getSecondOrderLogReturns(df.loc["2019-11-27":,"SPX"].tolist())
adf(CRdf_lret["SPX"], "COVID-SPX")

# Find ARIMA(p,1,q) models for log-return series that minimize AIC
# where p,q <= 5 and excluding ARIMA(0,1,0)
import statsmodels.tsa.arima_model as arima

def fit_ARIMA(timeseries, d=1):
    min_aic = 2 ** 32
    pdq = (6,d,6)
    results = []
#     print("Approximating model fitting to save time...")
    for p in range(6):
        for q in range(6):
            if p > 0 or q > 0:
                try:
                    model = arima.ARIMA(timeseries, (p,d,q))
                    fitted = model.fit(transparams=False,
                                       method="css",
                                       trend="nc",
                                       maxiter=50)
                    aic = arima.ARIMAResults(model, fitted.params).aic
#                     print("ARIMA(" + ",".join((str(p),str(d),str(q))) + ") - AIC: " + str(aic))                    
                    results.append([aic, (p,d,q)])
                except ValueError:
                    continue

    results = sorted(results, key=lambda x: x[0])
#     print("Refitting best model without approximation...")
    for result in results:
        try:
            p,d,q = result[1]
            model = arima.ARIMA(timeseries, (p,d,q))
            fitted = model.fit(transparams=False)
            residuals = arima.ARIMAResults(model, fitted.params).resid
            aic = arima.ARIMAResults(model, fitted.params).aic
            print("ARIMA(" + ",".join((str(p),str(d),str(q))) + ") - AIC: " + str(aic))
            return ((p,d,q), model, fitted, residuals)
        except ValueError:
            continue

# Quickly populate resultsdb with known values from above cell
def fit_arima(timeseries, pdq_tuple):
    model = arima.ARIMA(timeseries, pdq_tuple)
    fitted = model.fit(transparams=False)
    residuals = arima.ARIMAResults(model, fitted.params).resid
    return (pdq_tuple, model, fitted, residuals)

pdq = [[(1,1,4),(3,1,2),(1,1,5),(1,1,1)],
       [(4,1,5),(2,1,2),(1,1,5),(2,1,3)],
       [(4,1,2),(5,1,2),(2,1,3),(5,1,4)],
       [(4,2,1),(4,1,4),(5,1,1),(2,1,3)]]

# Box-Ljung Test of Autocorrelation in the ARIMA residuals.
v = resultsdb["ALL"]
data = v[1]
for col in data.columns:
    title = v[0] + " - " + col
    p,d,q = v[2][col][0]
    model = v[2][col][1]
    fitted = v[2][col][2]
    res = v[2][col][3]
    result = sm.stats.diagnostic.acorr_ljungbox(res, 
                                                lags=range(5),
                                                boxpierce=True, 
                                                model_df=p+q, 
                                                return_df=True)
    if result[(result["lb_pvalue"] < 0.01) &
             (result["bp_pvalue"] < 0.01)].size > 0:
        print(title + ": ARIMA-fitted residuals exhibit autocorrelation.")
    else:
        print(title + ": No autocorrelation.")

    sm.graphics.tsa.plot_acf(data[col], lags=40, title=title + ": Autocorrelation")
    sm.graphics.tsa.plot_pacf(data[col], lags=40, title=title + ": Partial Autocorrelation")

from statsmodels.graphics.gofplots import qqplot
# Jarque-Bera Test of Normality + QQ plots
v = resultsdb["ALL"]
data = v[1]
for col in data.columns:
    title = v[0] + " - " + col
    res = v[2][col][3]
    result = sm.stats.stattools.jarque_bera(res)
    print(title)
    print("JB statistic: " + str(result[0]) + ", p-value: " + str(result[1])
         + ", Skewness: " + str(result[2]) + ", Kurtosis: " + str(result[3]))
    if result[1] < 0.01:
        print(col + " is within the threshold for normal distribution.")
    else:
        print(col + " is non-normal.")
    print(qqplot(data[col]))

# Fit a ARIMA-GARCH(1,1) model for each asset
# and use it to forecast their 95%, 99% Value at Risk for 2019-2020. 
from arch import arch_model

def buildGARCH(arima_pkg, title, dataframe, date_cutoff="2020-05-01", dist='normal'):
    arima_res = pd.DataFrame({title: arima_pkg[3]},
                              index=dataframe.index[1:])
    am = arch_model(arima_res, mean='Zero', vol='Garch', p=1, o=0, q=1, dist=dist)
    res = am.fit(disp='off', last_obs=date_cutoff)
#     print(res.summary())
    if date_cutoff == "2020-05-01":
        fig = res.plot(annualize='D')
    return am, res

def VaR_parametric(asset, train_end_date, forecast_start_date, dist='skewt'):
    arima_pkg = resultsdb["ALL"][2][asset]
    data = resultsdb["ALL"][1][asset].copy()
    am, res = buildGARCH(arima_pkg, asset, data, date_cutoff=train_end_date, dist=dist)
    
    forecasts = res.forecast(start=forecast_start_date)
    cond_mean = forecasts.mean[forecast_start_date:]
    cond_var = forecasts.variance[forecast_start_date:]
    q = am.distribution.ppf([0.01,0.05], res.params[-2:])
    print(q)

    VaR = -cond_mean.values - np.sqrt(cond_var).values * q[None, :]
    VaR = pd.DataFrame(VaR, columns=['1%','5%'], index=cond_var.index)
    if len(resultsdb["ALL"]) == 3:
        resultsdb["ALL"].append({})
    if train_end_date == "2020-05-01" and forecast_start_date == "2007-01-01":
        resultsdb["ALL"][3][col] = VaR

    ax = VaR.plot(legend=True)
    ax.plot(data, color="#CCCCCC")
    ax.set_title(col + ': Parametric VaR')
    print(ax)

for col in resultsdb["ALL"][1].columns:
    VaR_parametric(col, train_end_date="2018-12-31", forecast_start_date="2019-01-01")
    VaR_parametric(col, train_end_date="2020-05-01", forecast_start_date="2007-01-01")

# Granger Causality: Risk Spillover
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import grangercausalitytests as granger_

VaRs = resultsdb["ALL"][3]

# for conf in "5%","1%":
def granger(cause, effect, conf="5%", lag=20):
    data = pd.DataFrame({cause: VaRs[cause][conf],
                            effect: VaRs[effect][conf]},
                            index=VaRs["SPX"].index)

    result1 = granger_(data[[effect, cause]], lag, verbose=False), (cause, effect)
    result2 = granger_(data[[cause, effect]], lag, verbose=False), (effect, cause)
    
    for result, order in result1, result2:
        yes_count = 0
        print(order[0] + " -> " + order[1])
        print("Lag, Confidence Level, F-statistic, p-value, Granger-Causality")
        for k,v in result.items():
            ftest = v[0]["params_ftest"]
            if ftest[1] < int(conf[0])*0.01:
                causality = "Yes"
                yes_count += 1
            else:
                causality = "No"
            print(str(k) + ": " + ", ".join((conf, str(ftest[0]), str(ftest[1]), causality)))
        if yes_count >= lag / 2:
            print("Granger-Causality exists from " + order[0] + " to " + order[1] + ".")
        else:
            print("No Granger-Causality exists from " + order[0] + " to " + order[1] + ".")
        print()
        
granger("SPX", "SSE", conf="1%")
granger("SPX", "CNY", conf="1%")
